ProMED-mail Rapporteur Mary Marshall

******
[2]
Date: 23 Sep 2008
Source: Herald Sun [edited]
<http://www.news.com.au/heraldsun/story/0,21985,24394003-5006021,00.html>


Equine influenza [EI], the virus that almost crippled the racing and
breeding industries a year ago, may not have been eradicated.

Even if it has, experts claim there is a significant risk of it
returning, bringing the racing industry to its knees, if Australia's
100 000-plus thoroughbreds are not vaccinated by the end of the year [2008].

The last reported case of EI was on Christmas Day last year [2007].

Two international experts, Australia's leading breeder John Messara
and former Federal Minister for Agriculture Peter McGauran, who
implemented the AUD 234 million [USD 195 million] EI assistance
package, will claim at an EI summit in Sydney tomorrow [24 Sep 2008]
that non-vaccination would put the industry in jeopardy.

They say there is no guarantee EI has been wiped out, a view
dismissed by Victoria's chief veterinary officer, Dr Hugh Millar.

"No chance ... it's completely gone," said Millar, who also dismissed
claims Australia was prone to another outbreak.

The federal government estimated that last year's [2007] EI outbreak
cost the racing and breeding industries more than AUD one billion
[USD 835 million]. It wiped out the Sydney spring carnival and went
close to devastating the breeding industry.

State chief veterinary officers, bio-security, racing and quarantine
officials, and representatives of various horse groups will debate
the vaccination issue tomorrow [24 Sep 2008]. State governments will
decide in November 2008 whether to vaccinate.

McGauran, now chief executive of Thoroughbred Breeders Australia,
said there was no guarantee EI did not exist in far-flung horse
populations. Dr David Powell, a leading equine vet with the
University of Kentucky, agreed, adding there was a remote chance EI
could again infiltrate the valuable thoroughbred population, possibly
from wild brumbies or other unchecked horses, in years to come.
"While unlikely, there is some possibility," he said.

Asked if he believed EI could still exist here, Messara said: "Absolutely."

McGauran, Messara and Powell said the global increase in horse
movement meant Australia was at further risk from EI, despite
tightening of quarantine since the outbreak. "We're tempting fate to
not believe EI will return in the future," McGauran said.

Messara, owner of Arrowfield Stud in the Hunter Valley and chairman
of breeding body Aushorse, added: "We cannot entirely rule out the
risk of human or systemic failure. In other countries, it has
returned when they haven't vaccinated."

Messara said the prospect of another outbreak was "too bad to
contemplate". "If it had gone on, the industry may not have survived.
That's how close we came."

Inoculation of Australia's horse population would cost AUD 10-15
million [USD 8.4-12.5 million], according to Messara, an annual flu
shot of about AUD 150 [USD 125] a horse.

Those against vaccination, including some state chief veterinary
officers and non-thoroughbred horse industries, such as equestrian
and standardbred, say it masks signs of EI.

They also argue that the disease has been eradicated and that the
lines of defense, including vastly more stringent quarantine, are
close to foolproof.

[Byline: Matt Stewart]

